    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-12-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-12-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="303"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d303">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.00/824</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Russia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_FDR1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Francis</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Petrograd</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-12-14">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 14, 1917</hi>
                        </date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received December 16, 1.20
                        a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2100. To-day’s bulletin, official organ of Soviet, says <persName
                        corresp="#p_TLDB1">Trotsky</persName> in speech at Grenadier Regiment said:
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>
                            <persName corresp="#p_JBGWV1">Judson</persName> came to us and said that
                            it isn’t true that England is preparing to deprive us of supplies and
                                <persName corresp="#p_RLCR1">Colonel Robins</persName> said that he
                            had never seen a firmer government. He thinks that his Government will
                            be the first to recognize us and will propose the services of American
                            engineers to regulate the railways and automobiles for the
                            transportation of food supplies. The matter assuredly does not lie in a
                            general love for us but in the fact that America and England on the one
                            hand and America and Japan on the other hand are interested in having us
                            remain a market for their goods.</p>
                        <p>We have been threatened that Japan, as a punishment for the negotiations,
                            would annex Siberia. But if Japan could take Siberia from us she would
                            do this independently of the war and of the armistice. However, she does
                            not do this because America does not allow it.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_FDR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Francis</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
